          "body": "Jethro's counsel in verses 19-23 is one of the most practically detailed governance prescriptions in the Bible. It has three layers. First, Moses' irreplaceable function is clarified: he remains the people's representative before God (18:19) and the teacher of statutes and laws (18:20). These roles cannot be delegated because they require the unique mediatorial authority Moses holds. Second, the delegated function is defined: capable men, organized in a four-tier hierarchy of thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens (18:21), will handle routine disputes. The qualifications for these men — capability, fear of God, trustworthiness, hatred of dishonest gain (18:21) — form the Old Testament's foundational profile of judicial character. Notably, fear of God heads the list. Justice is a theological virtue before it is a legal procedure. Third, the principle of subsidiarity governs the system: 'every major dispute they will bring to you, but every minor dispute they themselves will judge' (18:22). The most consequential condition in the entire prescription is 18:23 — 'if you do this thing and God so commands you.' Jethro's wisdom is human; its authority is conditional on divine ratification. He does not counsel Moses to act immediately; he counsels him to inquire of God whether this is His design. This is wisdom epistemic humility: good advice awaits divine sanction before becoming binding policy."
