        "number": 2,
        "title": "The diagnosis — faithful work done unsustainably is not good",
        "range": "18:13-18",
        "excerpt": "Moses' father-in-law said to him, 'The thing that you are doing is not good. You will surely wear out, both yourself and these people who are with you, for the task is too heavy for you; you cannot do it alone.'",
        "body": "The judicial scene Jethro observes in 18:13-14 is not a picture of corruption, laziness, or unfaithfulness. Moses is diligently adjudicating disputes and teaching the statutes and laws of God (18:16). His stated intention is noble: 'the people come to me to inquire of God' (18:15). The problem Jethro identifies is structural, not moral — and that distinction is crucial for interpretation.\n\nJethro's verdict — 'the thing that you are doing is not good' (18:17) — uses the Hebrew *tov*, the word that anchors God's own evaluation of creation in Genesis 1. What is happening in Moses' court is not *tov*. The reason given is practical: 'you will surely wear out' (*naval*, 18:18 — the same word used of a withered leaf or a faded garment; exhaustion to the point of uselessness) 'both yourself and these people.' The burden is too heavy for one man; it will break both the carrier and the carried.\n\nThis passage has generated rich theological reflection in the history of interpretation. John Calvin, commenting on the parallel in Deuteronomy 1, observes that Moses' error was not lack of faith but lack of wisdom: 'God does not always immediately suggest to His servants what is best for them.' The acquisition of wisdom — including structural wisdom about the limits of one person's capacity — is a genuine process, and it is not shameful to learn it from an unexpected source. The text models that Moses' authority did not inoculate him against institutional blindness.\n\nThe canonical parallel in Numbers 11:14-17 is illuminating. When Moses later tells God 'I alone am not able to carry all this people' (Numbers 11:14), God responds by distributing the Spirit on seventy elders — the same pattern, initiated this time from God Himself. God ratifies in Numbers what Jethro prescribed in Exodus. Delegation is not a merely human managerial strategy; it is God's own design for the governance of His people.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Naval* (wear out, 18:18) — to sink, to wither, to become a *nabal* (the fool-figure in Proverbs whose strength collapses). The word carries connotations of disgraceful collapse, not merely fatigue. *Kaved* (heavy, 18:18) — the same root as the LORD's 'glory' (*kavod*) and Pharaoh's 'hardened' heart; the weight of the judicial burden is, literally and theologically, too glorious for one man to bear alone."
